Fresh-eyes review complete for `src/blog/people/drafts/Jack-Antonoff.md`. The notes are appended as a `FRESH EYES REVIEW (2026-07-11)` comment block at the bottom of the file.

The two biggest issues I flagged:

1. **The fun. era is missing from the main body.** A reader who knows Antonoff expects "We Are Young" / "Some Nights" — it's how he got famous, won his first Grammys, and entered Taylor Swift's orbit. The body jumps from Steel Train in 2001 straight to Bleachers and 13 Grammys; fun. only appears as a parenthetical in the Rabbit Hole. It's also a wasted thesis beat: he got famous inside someone else's band ("It wasn't my band"), which is the untested-room problem in biographical form.

2. **The talent itself is never explained.** The working notes admit the type doesn't account for 40+ albums of output, and the body sidesteps it too — his musicianship is described only through the critics' complaint list. The piece explains why artists trust him, but not what he does once trusted.

Also worth a look: the Kendrick/"Luther" collaboration is undersold (one clause, when it's the strongest counter to the sameness critique), the Antonoff-ification section closes its argument three times, and the closing section discusses the wedding song without acknowledging the separation the reader just learned about one section earlier. On the plus side, the cold open, the floor-plan section, and the ragtime ending are all keepers — I marked those to preserve. No body edits were made, per the command.
